I completed an initial exploratory analysis on a direct Google Play review scrape covering 30,000 reviews across 5 apps. The current sample is English/US only, spans March 20 to April 6, 2026, and is concentrated, with each app accounting for 20% of all reviews.

A few key takeaways stood out. The rating distribution is strongly skewed positive: 63.31% of reviews are 5-star, while 19.73% are 1-star. Review text is generally short, with a median length of 4 words and 19 characters. There is also a clear pattern that lower-rated reviews tend to be more informative: median length is 12–14 words for 1–2 star reviews, versus 3–4 words for 4–5 star reviews. Developer replies are relatively sparse overall, but they appear more often on low-rated reviews than on high-rated ones.

From a data quality perspective, the scrape itself looks structurally clean: there are no empty reviews, no duplicate review IDs, and no invalid zero ratings. The main issue is not broken records, but low-information and repetitive text. About 22.46% of reviews are single-token, 38.21% are two words or fewer, 15.21% are under five characters, and 15.97% fall into generic boilerplate praise. In addition, 31.17% of review text is duplicated somewhere in the dataset, with 27.14% duplicated within the same app, which suggests a high volume of repeated short reactions such as “good,” “great,” and similar low-value comments. Non-ASCII characters appear in 19.8% of reviews, which likely reflects emoji and other Unicode characters rather than necessarily a language problem in this sample.

My current view is that Google Play remains a strong source because the review-level structure is useful and the scrape is technically clean, but it will need a processing layer before downstream use. The most important steps will be to preserve raw text, normalize Unicode and whitespace, flag or filter ultra-short and punctuation-only reviews depending on the task, deduplicate by review ID, and create filtered subsets for sentiment analysis versus more substantive topic or issue mining.

The main caveat is representativeness: this first pass only covers 5 apps and is limited to en/us, so it is best treated as an initial dataset-understanding step rather than a final production sample.